name: Percy Venable
comments: West Coast producer and composer, but also active in 1920s Chicago, where he worked with Louis Armstrong, Earl (Fatha) Hines and Duke Ellington.

name: Les Octaves
comments: Vocalist act: Léda et Gérard Boehler, Jean-Marie Ploye, Michel Joubert, Gérard Fardet and Bernard Guyot

name: Justine Pelmelay
comments: Dutch singer that reached the 15th place at the Eurovision Song Contest in 1989 with the song "Blijf Zoals Je Bent".

name: Walter Werzowa
comments: Composer and producer. Also owner of LA music production studio Musikvergnuegen.

name: David Bell [US1]
comments: Pastor and Christian songwriter from Texas

name: Marcos Witt
comments: Christian music singer and pastor considered the most influential and famous Spanish speaking figure of Christian music

name: The White N3rd
comments: Songwriter and pop producer from Manchester

name: Micke Littwold
comments: Guitarist, singer, songwriter, arranger, producer and teacher

name: Dave Damiani
comments: Singer, songwriter, and producer based out of Los Angeles, California

name: Dan Lindén
comments: Pianist/keyboarder mainly active as a live artist on the Swedish west coast. Lindén also appeard as a back-up musician for a nnumber of Swedish top artists.

name: Denver Harbor
comments: Alt rock band from San Diego

name: A Small Victory
comments: Punk rock/emo band from Buford, Georgia

name: Banda do Corpo de Bombeiros
comments: Fire brigade marching band. Aka "Corpo de Bombeiros Militar do Distrito Federal" (CBMDF).

name: Errol Buddle
comments: Jazz musician from Adelaide. A multi-instrumentalist he played banjo and mandolin before taking up saxophones, clarinets, flutes,  oboe and English horn. He was known as the first jazz bassonist in the world.

name: I Cavalieri del Re
comments: Pop group, specialized in children's music.

name: Alice Merton
comments: German-Canadian singer and songwriter born in Frankfurt

name: Mabel
comments: English-Swedish singer and songwriter, born in Malaga, Spain, and based in London

name: Gringos Locos
comments: Hard rock band not only succesful at home, but particularly popular in the UK - where they were the first Finnish band to play the  Wembley Arena - and in the US. The band consisted a.o. of Ben Granfelt, Muddy Manninen, Masa Maijanen, Miri Miettinen, Pete Asiala and Richard G. Johnson.

name: Hovet
comments: Originally a handpicked band to back Lars Winnerbäck, the group is also active in its own rights.

name: Wintley Phipps
comments: Gospel singer and ordained minister. Phipps was born in Trinidad and Tobago, then moved to Canada at an early age before eventually settling in the United States.

name: Marita Lindquist
comments: Marita Lindqvist or Lindquist was an author of many children's books. Born in Helsinki she was of the Swedish-speaking population of Finland. In addition, she wrote  song lyrics, illustrated books and worked as a translator, materials writer, producer, editor and journalist.

name: Crossing Borders
comments: Jazz quintet combining jazz vocalist/pianist Jennifer Scott, bassist Rene Worst, saxophonist/vocalist Kristen Strom, guitarist Scott Sorkin and drummer Jason Lewis.

name: The Half Moon Jug Band
comments: Three man band formed in Maine. Members include Troy R. Bennett, "Frost" Steve Brewer and Steve "Clean Fill" Clegg.

name: Jesse Larson
comments: Vocalist who competed on the twelfth season of NBC's talent show, The Voice, in the spring of 2017

name: Paul Heyse
comments: Author born  in Berlin, who was awarded with the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1910.

name: Taylor Alexander
comments: Nashville-based singer-songwriter who competed on the twelfth season of NBC's talent show, The Voice, in the spring of 2017

name: TSoul
comments: R&B vocalist who competed on the twelfth season of NBC's talent show, The Voice, in the spring of 2017

name: Josh Hoyer
comments: R&B and funk vocalist who competed on the twelfth season of NBC's talent show, The Voice, in the spring of 2017

name: Josh LaFayette
comments: Designer, art director and composer based in Atlanta, Georgia

name: Serena Joy
comments: Gospel vocalist based in Waco, Texas

name: Late Night Alumni
comments: House group comprising of Becky Jean Williams, John Hancock, Bjarnson and Kaskade

name: Gabrielle Current
comments: Singer and model from Los Angeles

name: David Broekman
comments: Film composer, songwriter and conductor born in Leiden.

name: Durward Lely
comments: Scottish opera singer and actor primarily known as the creator of five tenor roles in Gilbert and Sullivan's comic operas including the part of Nanki-Poo in the 1885 comic opera The Mikado .

name: Jessie Bond
comments: English singer and actress best known for creating the mezzo-soprano soubrette roles in the Gilbert and Sullivan comic operas. She spent twenty years on the stage, the bulk of them with the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company.

name: Frederick Bovill
comments: Operatic baritone of the late Victorian era. In his short career, he created the roles of Pish-Tush in Gilbert and Sullivan's comic opera hit The Mikado (1885) and the Squire in Sullivan's romantic opera Ivanhoe (1891).

name: Karl Farkas
comments: Actor and cabaret artist born  in Vienna.

name: Géza Herczeg
comments: Hungarian-American playwright and screenwriter born in Budapest, who was also a newspaper publisher and a war correspondent.

name: Quarteto Moderno
comments: Jazz quartet: Andréa Dutra / Zé Luiz Maia / Kleberson Caetano	/ Paulo Malaguti Pauleira.

name: Leif Janzon
comments: Librettist, theatre historian and translator, a. o. of Norman Mailer and Seamus Heaney.

name: Elsie Griffin
comments: English opera singer, best known for her performances in the soprano roles of the Savoy Operas with the (Rupert) D'Oyly Carte Opera Company. Savoy opera was a style of comic opera that developed in Victorian England in the late 19th century, with W. S. Gilbert and Arthur Sullivan as the original and most successful practitioners.

name: Derek Oldham
comments: English singer and actor born in Accrington, Lancashire, best known for his performances in the tenor roles of the Savoy Operas with the (Rupert) D'Oyly Carte Opera Company. Savoy opera was a style of comic opera that developed in Victorian England in the late 19th century, with W. S. Gilbert and Arthur Sullivan as the original and most successful practitioners.

name: Rupert D'Oyly Carte
comments: English hotelier, theater owner and impresario born in Hampstead, London, best known as proprietor of the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company and the Savoy Hotel, London from 1913 to 1948.
